# **1. JPY FUNDING RATES: HOW THEY REALLY WORK**

### **Key JPY funding rates**

* **TONA** (Tokyo Overnight Average) — real overnight rate
* **Call rate** — interbank funding
* **BoJ policy rate** — currently the policy anchor (from negative to slowly positive)

### **How Japan is different**

In the US/Europe:

* Central bank sets a policy rate → money markets transmit it → yields adjust.

In Japan:

* Policy rate barely moves.
* **Money markets are massively distorted** by excess liquidity from QQE.
* There is a gigantic stock of **excess reserves**.

### 🇯🇵 **So what does a BoJ rate hike actually do?**

It affects:

* Banks’ willingness to lend JPY
* Hedging costs for insurers
* Cross-currency basis (USDJPY funding)
* Short-end JGB yields

But **it barely tightens liquidity**, because:

* The system is already “flooded” with BoJ reserves.
* Japan’s transmission = **signaling → expectations → FX → imported inflation**, not credit tightening.

---

# **2. LIQUIDITY IN JAPAN: WHY IT’S A TRANSMISSION CHANNEL, NOT A TARGET**

### **2.1 JGB liquidity is structurally thin**

* BoJ owns >50% of JGBs.
* Banks/pensions hold most of the rest.
* Free float is minimal.

### Implication:

* When global yields rise, JGB yields **cannot keep up** (because BoJ doesn’t allow it).
* Liquidity evaporates → violent moves → policy intervention.

### **2.2 The liquidity channel IS Japan’s monetary policy**

In the US:

> Policy transmission = funding → credit → demand → inflation.

In Japan:

> Policy transmission = liquidity → yields → FX → imported inflation.

This is crucial:
**JPY is the main transmission channel**, not domestic credit.

---

# **3. CROSS-CURRENCY BASIS: THE HEART OF JAPAN’S FUNDING TRANSMISSION**

![Image](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303913248/figure/fig4/AS%3A372057964597251%401465716939202/year-cross-currency-basis-swaps-against-USD-01012007-25112015-bps.png?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

![Image](https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ikYL4UVJ.PJw/v3/piL.vZNnk8fG1FJf0SN7xW9FmdjS0dnCrU/-1x-1.png?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

![Image](https://storage.googleapis.com/web-content.oanda.com/images/USDJPY_chart_of_the_week_by_OANDA.width-1400.png?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

The **USDJPY cross-currency basis (CCB)** reflects the cost of borrowing USD against JPY collateral.

### **3.1 Why basis matters**

When US–Japan rate differential widens:

* USD becomes expensive to hedge into JPY
* Basis widens (more negative for USDJPY)

This increases **FX hedging costs** for:

* Life insurers (big)
* Pension funds
* Banks
* Corporates

### **3.2 Transmission via hedging behaviour**

When hedging costs rise:

* Insurers **reduce USD hedges** → they hold FX risk → USDJPY goes up
* They avoid buying USD assets on a hedged basis
* They prefer buying **unhedged foreign assets** → capital outflow → JPY weakness

When hedging costs fall:

* Insurers **increase hedging** → buy JPY → USDJPY goes down
* Capital flows return → JPY strengthens

This creates **procyclical FX dynamics**:

* Rising global yields → USDJPY up
* Falling hedging costs in recessions → USDJPY down sharply

---

# **4. HOW BOJ POLICY IMPACTS FUNDING MARKETS**

### **4.1 Policy Rate → TONA → Call Market → Repo Market**

A BoJ hike:

* Lifts TONA slightly
* Increases cost of JPY cash
* Makes JPY-funded carry trades a bit less attractive
* But because reserves are abundant, the hike doesn’t “tighten liquidity”

### **4.2 BoJ QE/QT → Collateral scarcity → Repo dynamics**

When BoJ buys JGBs:

* JGB collateral becomes scarce
* Repo specialness increases
* Funding markets distort further
* Basis can tighten (hedged USD investment becomes cheaper)

When BoJ reduces purchases:

* Collateral shortage eases
* Market regains function
* Yields can rise more freely

**This is why the BoJ constantly adjusts Rinban (bond-buying ops).**

### **4.3 YCC → Liquidity fragmentation**

Under YCC:

* The 10Y becomes a *policy instrument*
* Liquidity around 10Y dries up
* Trading shifts to swaps and futures
* Basis markets become primary transmission channel

